            "creation_date": 1326831929,
            "body": "<p>Arrays in java are objects, so you can write a method that receive one Object and test using the \"instanceof\" function.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class MethodTest {\n\npublic static void main(String[] args) {\n    String[] tst = new String[]{\"SOME\",\"TEXT\"};\n    doSomething( tst );\n    doSomething(\"TEST\");\n}\n\npublic static void doSomething( Object o ) {\n    if( o instanceof String ) {\n        System.out.println( (String) o );\n    } else if( o instanceof String[] ) {\n        String something[] = (String[]) o;\n        for( String s : something ) {\n            System.out.println( s );\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>But I think two methods will be a best approach...<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8901247,
            "question_id": 8901109
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f1ed2b0c87f602ef30229f5c4b04eff6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 152622,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 367273,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/367273/npe",
                "reputation": 503179,
                "display_name": "NPE",
                "accept_rate": 96
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1326831849,
            "creation_date": 1326831849,
            "body": "<p>From your description of the problem, you're almost certainly better off writing two overloaded methods.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is unclear what -- if anything -- would be gained by combining them into one. However, doing that would probably require a non-trivial amount of effort and the result will likely be pretty convoluted.<\/p>\n\n<p>Besides, a single method that can take both an array and a <code>String<\/code> would have to take <code>Object<\/code> as its argument. Once you accept <code>Object<\/code>, people will be able to call your method with <em>lots<\/em> of things it won't know how to deal with; instead of compile-time failures, the combined method would have to fail at run time.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8901231,
            "question_id": 8901109
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c97bba51cc8f938dcc806703fb55efc2?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 913338,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 946679,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/946679/zeller",
